{"query":"Tell me about Kenyan garden ants","response":{"answer":"Kenyan garden ants, also known as *Pheidole megacephala*, are a species of ant that is commonly found in East Africa, including Kenya. Here's some information about them:\n\n1. Identification: These ants have a distinctive appearance with large heads (giant eyes) compared to their bodies, which gives them the name \"big-headed ants.\" They are usually light brown or reddish-brown.\n\n2. Habitat: As suggested by their common name, they can be found in gardens, parks, and other urban areas. However, they also inhabit a wide range of environments, including forests, savannas, and even deserts.\n\n3. Behavior:\n   - They are omnivorous, feeding on both plant matter and insects.\n   - These ants often build their nests in soil or under objects like rocks, logs, or debris.\n   - They can be found foraging during the day and night.\n   - They are known to farm aphids for honeydew, a sugary substance produced by these insects.\n\n4. Colony structure: Like many ant species, *Pheidole megacephala* has a complex social structure with different castes:\n   - Queens (fertile females)\n   - Workers (sterile females that perform most of the colony's work)\n   - Males (whose sole purpose is to mate with queens)\n\n5. Reproduction: Colonies can produce multiple queens, which allows for rapid expansion and spread.\n\n6. Economic impact: While they are not considered a major pest in Kenya, these ants can sometimes become problematic when they invade homes or agricultural areas. They can also compete with native ant species for resources.\n\n7. Spread: *Pheidole megacephala* is an invasive species that has spread to many parts of the world outside its native range, including Africa, Asia, Australia, and parts of North America.\n\n8. Control: In some cases, these ants may be controlled using baits or other pest management techniques, but this can vary depending on local regulations and environmental factors.\n\nThese garden ants play an important role in their ecosystems as decomposers and predators, but their presence can sometimes cause issues for humans.","model":"qwen2.5:7b-instruct","treatments":[{"treatments_id":319253,"treatmentId":"03E4F47BDB646913FF122728FDC0FB04","zenodoDep":7797874,"treatmentTitle":"Pseudapis kuhlmanni Pauly & Monks & Polaszek 2023, sp. nov.","treatmentAuthor":"Polaszek, Andrew","articleTitle":"Two new species of Pseudapis Kirby, 1900 (Hymenoptera: Halictidae: Nomiinae) from Oman","articleAuthor":"Pauly, Alain, Monks, Joseph & Polaszek, Andrew","journalYear":2023,"journalTitle":"Zootaxa","publicationDate":"2023-04-04","status":"sp. nov.","genus":"Pseudapis","species":"kuhlmanni","score":0.5495662126207966,"images":[{"httpUri":"https://zenodo.org/record/7797882/files/figure.png","captionText":"FIGURE 3. Pseudapis kuhlmanni, sp. nov., male.A, habitus; B, head; C, mesosoma; D, propodeum; E, first tergum; F, metasoma."},{"httpUri":"https://zenodo.org/record/7797884/files/figure.png","captionText":"FIGURE 4. Structures of males; A, Hind leg of P. kuhlmanni sp. nov.; B, Hind leg of P. interstitinervis; C, Apical lobes of sternum V of P. kuhlmanni; D, Apical lobes of sternum V of P. interstitinervis; E, Sternum V and apical membranes of the genitalia of P. kuhlmanni; F, Genitalia of P. kuhlmanni in dorsal view."},{"httpUri":"https://zenodo.org/record/7797888/files/figure.png","captionText":"FIGURE 5. Pseudapis kuhlmanni sp. nov., female. A, dorsal view; B, lateral view."},{"httpUri":"https://zenodo.org/record/7797880/files/figure.png","captionText":"FIGURE 2. Pseudapis kuhlmanni, sp. nov., male."}]},{"treatments_id":149734,"treatmentId":"03AC878989404D526E259621FD27E5C3","zenodoDep":10833092,"treatmentTitle":"Cruranthura viridis Shiraki & Kakui 2024, sp. nov.","treatmentAuthor":"Kakui, Keiichi","articleTitle":"Description of a New Cruranthura Species from the Miyako Islands, Japan, with Its DNA Barcode (Isopoda: Anthuroidea: Paranthuridae)","articleAuthor":"Shir